    "body": "so for daily and lower freq these should be equivalent.\n\nhowever, for other freqs, These produce different results as they are conceptually different operations.\n`.shift` moves each point to the new freq, adjusting for new freq (snapping it). While simple addition doesn't normalize.\n\n```\nIn [29]: ts.index+np.timedelta64(5,'M')                              \nOut[29]: \nDatetimeIndex(['2000-06-03 04:25:30', '2000-06-04 04:25:30', '2000-06-05 04:25:30', '2000-06-06 04:25:30', '2000-06-07 04:25:30', '2000-06-10 04:25:30', '2000-06-11 04:25:30', '2000-06-12 04:25:30',\n               '2000-06-13 04:25:30', '2000-06-14 04:25:30', \n               ...\n               '2038-09-18 04:25:30', '2038-09-19 04:25:30', '2038-09-20 04:25:30', '2038-09-21 04:25:30', '2038-09-22 04:25:30', '2038-09-25 04:25:30', '2038-09-26 04:25:30', '2038-09-27 04:25:30',\n               '2038-09-28 04:25:30', '2038-09-29 04:25:30'],\n              dtype='datetime64[ns]', length=10000, freq='B', tz=None)\n\nIn [30]: ts.shift(5,'M').index\nOut[30]: \nDatetimeIndex(['2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', '2000-05-31', \n               ...\n               '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-08-31', '2038-09-30'],\n              dtype='datetime64[ns]', length=10000, freq=None, tz=None)\n```\n\nSo I _think_ you could shortcut the shift to do a timedelta operation with the passed freq if its daily or less.\n\nWant to do a pull-request?\n"
  },
